Treat him as such for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Baun was excellent in Week 10, notching three solos, five assists, one tackle for loss, two forced fumbles, and one fumble recovery. Baun has pushed his way back into the LB1 ranks with his three game stretch and should be counted as one for a plus matchup on Thursday Night Football.
Speed was excellent in Week 10, racking up four solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. The LB4 on the season, Speed is a top-five option regardless of opponent.

Sherwood was excellent in Week 10, notching seven solos, 10 assists, and one tackle for loss. Sherwood has been elite since stepping in for CJ Mosley and has been an LB1 in fppg. Start him as one for Week 11 despite the tough on-paper matchup against Indianapolis.

Quincy was excellent in Week 10, racking up three solos, seven assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Quincy has strung three strong performances together and is trending upwards as an LB2 option. Treat him as such for Week 11 against the Colts.

Daiyan Henley went bonkers in Week 10, racking up 11 solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Henley has recorded six or more solos in just five of his 10 games this season, but has done so in each of his last three contests, pushing him into the top-20 conversation. Treat him as an elite LB2 play for a Week 11 against Cincinnati.

Azeez was excellent in Week 10, racking up five solos, three assists, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. He had been sidelined since Week 7 with a knee injury but is back in the middle and ready to play a pivotal role in the Texans' stretch run. Tap him as an LB2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Cashman returned to action in Week 10, putting up three solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 80 percent of the snaps. He should be back closer to an everydown role in Week 11 and can be trusted as an LB3 with LB2 upside. He will be an LB2 once he is back to an everydown role, but for now, temper expectations as far as his floor is concerned. Add and start Cashman as an LB3 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Overshown exploded in Week 10, racking up eight solos, three assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. The solo count is a welcomed sight, but Overshown has shined even without high solo counts in recent weeks, tallying six total tackles for loss over his last three contests. Oveshown has worked his way into high-end LB2 territory and should be treated as one for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Houston Texans. Add Overshown everywhere; he is a must-start until he cools down.

Brooks was excellent in Week 10, racking up six solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Brooks has recorded five or more solos in three of his last four and four or more in each. TReat Brooks as an LB2 option as long as he is cooking. Start him with confidence for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Gibbens was at it again in Week 10, racking up 10 solos and five assists. Gibbens has been excellent since the Ernest Jones trade and will continue to start even when Jerome Baker is ready for action. He remains a risky play due to a comparable talent behind him, but the team has no plans on making the switch while Gibbens is playing well. Add and start Gibbens as an LB3 play where needed.

Queen was excellent in Week 10, tallying six solos, one assist, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Queen has not made quite the same IDP impact that he did in his contract season in Baltimore, but still makes for a solid LB2/3 play. Treat him as a top-25 option for a Week 11 revenge game against the Baltimore Ravens.

Lloyd was excellent in Week 10, tallying nine solos and seven assists. Lloyd has recorded five or more solos in just five of his 10 games this season but in two straight. Tap him as an LB3 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Tavai showed up again in Week 10, this time notching seven solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Tavai is producing at his highest level of the season, recording six or more solos and a sack or a pick in his last two contests. Tavai is still safer to deploy as an LB3 but can be started as an LB2 in a pinch for Week 11, thanks to a plus matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.  Add Tavai where needed.

To'oTo'o showed up in Week 10, tallying three solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. To'oTo'o has been better in real life than in fantasy and is more LB4/flex than LB3. Treat him as such where possible despite the heavy bye week.

Parsons was excellent in his return to the field, tallying two solos, two sacks, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Micah was struggling before the injury, so hopefully, the time off has provided some fuel he can utilize for the rest of the season. Jennings was excellent in Week 10, racking up four solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Jennings is a solid LB3/4 option for Week 11, thanks to both his strong recent play and a plus matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Branch was excellent in Week 10, notching six solos, four assists, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. The DB3 on the season, Branch is a top-five option regardless of opponent. Treat him as such for Week 11 against Jacksonville.

Cross was excellent in Week 10, tallying seven solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. The DB4 on the season, continue to start Cross as a top-10 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the New York Jets.

Byard was excellent in Week 10, notching five solos, six assists, and one pass defended. Byard has recorded four or more solos in six of his nine contests and has added a sack, a pick, two fumbles forced, and three tackles for loss, boosting him to DB1 numbers on the season. Treat Byard as an elite DB2 for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Chinn was excellent in Week 10, racking up six solos, seven assists, one fumble recovery, one interception, and one pass defended. Chinn has recorded six or more solos in three of his last five games and is back in the DB2 mix. Treat him as such for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles. Add Chinn wherever possible.

Rapp showed up in Week 10, tallying five solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Rapp has picked up his production in recent weeks and can be trusted as a DB2 option as long as he is cooking. Treat him as such for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Adams was excellent in Week 10, tallying five solos and five assists. It was a strong return to the field after being sidelined with a hamstring injury and puts him squarely back in the DB2/3 mix going forward. Treat him as a DB2 for Week 11, thanks to a tasty matchup against the Indianapolis Colts. Add Adams where needed.

CJGJ showed up in Week 10, racking up two solos, five assists, one interception, and one pass defended. CJGJ hasn't been the DB1 level producer we expected in his return to Philadelphia but has still provided DB3 level value, thanks to some spike weeks. Treat him as a DB3 option for Thursday Night Football.

Tyrann was excellent in Week 10, tallying three solos, one interception, and three passes defended. Mathieu has been inconsistent after a hot start to the season but still boasts DB2 upside with the right matchup. He has one of those matchups in Week 11 against the Cleveland Browns. Add and start Tyrann where needed.

Amadi was excellent in Week 10, racking up nine solos, three tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Ugo got his first start of the season with Marshon Lattimore traded to the Cardinals and could continue to provide dividends at nickel. He should be treated as a CB1/2 or DB3 option going forward. Start him with confidence for Week 11 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Nazeeh was excellent in his second start, racking up six solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. He should continue to be an IDP asset across from Trent McDuffie, but outside corners will usually be inconsistent. Treat him as a CB3/DB5 at best until he proves he can produce consistently. Look elsewhere for your Week 11 DB3.

Ward showed up in Week 10, tallying four solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended. Ward has dealt with injuries this season but has offered DB3/4 value when he has been active. Tap him as a DB3 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Savage showed up in Week 10, racking up three solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. This was by far his best fantasy outing of the season and does not change the fact that he is more of a deep league depth piece than someone you want to plug into lineups. Look elsewhere for your Week 11 DB3/4 despite the plus matchup against the Detroit Lions.
